Information
------------------------------

Football Hooligans And Proud
Featuring frank and honest interviews with the perpetrators themselves, this programme shines a light into the underworld of 21st-century hooliganism.
Die-hard Rochdale AFC fan Lee, 37, has just started his third soccer banning order, and there is nothing he likes more than a scuffle.
&quot;At the age of thirteen, I started to want to fight. I love fear. That's just me. I'm after, like, danger...Football violence is a feeling on its own,&quot; he says. 
27-year-old Jay is a white van man who lives with his wife and a cat called Mohammed. He is a lifelong Bristol City fan and a self-confessed football yob.
Jay believes that being a hooligan is a way of life:
&quot;For some reason, football hooliganism is deemed awful. Other people like tennis or rock-climbing-that's where they get their buzz. I need something more, something what's wrong because it feels right. It's a free country...I do what I want,&quot; says Jay.

